Humanitarian blind spots in Western climate change policy and discourse
                    Muhammad Uzair Qamar 
            ORCID: orcid.org/0009-0006-5661-89951,2 & Faisal Baig 
            ORCID: orcid.org/0000-0002-9915-678X3

Nature Climate Change

(2026)Cite this article

Subjects

            Climate-change mitigationGovernance

Access through your institution







                        Buy or subscribe

Contemporary climate discourse has largely assumed a top-down orientation, engaging mainly the scientific and policy spheres while marginalizing the experiences of those directly affected, and limiting the incorporation of bottom-up perspectives into policy formulation. Such an approach risks perpetuating the perception of climate change as a political issue primarily concerning elite, Western nations, rather than recognizing it as a global humanitarian crisis. For example, a recent review article provided a comprehensive review of the politics of climate policy, focusing on the phenomenon of ‘green backlash’ and emphasizing the economic dimensions of climate policy1. In our view, however, this framing has repeatedly proven insufficient and is unlikely to yield durable results. A shift away from narrow political and economic grounds towards survival- and humanitarian-oriented narratives — ones that resonate more naturally on an emotional and psychological level2 — is needed. Global evidence suggests that humanitarian appeals more effectively mobilize public and political support3, reframing the debate from economic trade-offs to the universal imperative of safeguarding lives, ecosystems and future generations.While policy-oriented recommendations directed at decision-makers remain essential, meaningful engagement with affected communities in fragile economies is equally critical to ensure that policies reflect the lived realities and priorities of those most affected by climate change. Ideally, climate action should be driven by public leadership; sustained public participation can cultivate broader legitimacy and reduce resistance when climate-related policies are implemented. Grounded in empirically observable events, this perspective focuses on the immediate, localized implications of climate change for human well-being — particularly threats to basic needs, health and livelihoods in fragile economies — and translates these realities into accessible narratives that resonate across diverse audiences, ensuring that the perspectives of vulnerable communities inform the global climate narrative. In doing so, it contributes bottom-up perspectives with the lived experiences through which climate change is most acutely understood.



